03977nam a22005535i 9780226216089DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014027338  a97802262160897 a10.7208/97802262160892doi  a(DE-B1597)550018  a(OCoLC)1090496212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQK50b.S78 2014 4aQK50 7aGAR0000002bisacsh04a5801 aStuppy, Wolfgang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWonders of the Plant Kingdom :bA Microcosm Revealed /cWolfgang Stuppy, Madeline Harley, Rob Kesseler. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (157 p.) :b250 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tThe Incredible Life of Plants -- tPrecious dust -- tFruits and Seeds -- tPhytopia -- tThe ‘Making Of’ Wonders of the Plant Kingdom: How Science Becomes Art -- tThe Millennium Seed Bank: The World’s Largest Plant Conservation Initiative -- tAppendices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCompared to the obvious complexity of animals, plants at a glance seem relatively simple in form. But that simplicity is deceptive: the plants around us are the result of millennia of incredible evolutionary adaptations that have allowed them to survive, and thrive, under wildly changing conditions and in remarkably specific ecological niches. Much of this innovation, however, is invisible to the naked eye. With Wonders of the Plant Kingdom, the naked eye gets an unforgettable boost. A stunning collaboration between science and art, this gorgeous book presents hundreds of images of plants taken with a scanning electron microscope and hand-colored by artist Rob Kesseler to reveal the awe-inspiring adaptations all around us. The surface of a peach—with its hairs, or trichomes, and sunken stomata, or breathing pores—emerges from these pages in microscopic detail. The dust-like seeds of the smallest cactus species in the world, the Blossfeldia liliputana—which measures just twelve millimeters fully grown—explode here with form, color, and character, while the flower bud of a kaffir lime, cross-sectioned, reveals the complex of a flower bud with the all-important pistil in the center. Accompanying these extraordinary images are up-to-date explanations of the myriad ways that these plants have ensured their own survival—and, by proxy, our own. Gardeners and science buffs alike will marvel at this wholly new perspective on the world of plant diversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBotany. 0aPlants. 0aSeeds. 7aGARDENING / General.2bisacsh1 aHarley, Madeline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKesseler, Rob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226216089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226216089.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles